and distribution. Digital Encounters explores the influence of an increasingly networked world on contemporary Latin American cultural production. Drawing on a spectrum of case studies, the contributors to this volume examine literature, art, and political activism as they dialogue with programming languages, social media platforms, online publishing, and geospatial metadata. Implicit within these connections are questions of power, privilege, and stratification. The book critically examines issues of inequitable access and data privacy, technology’s capacity to divide people from one another, and the digital space as a site of racialized and gendered violence. Through an expansive approach to the study of connectivity, Digital Encounters illustrates how new connections – between analog and digital, human and machine, print text and pixel – alter representations of self, Other, and world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and technologyzLatin America. 0aArt, Latin Americany21st century. 0aDigital mediazLatin America. 0aInternet and activismzLatin America. 0aLatin American literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and technologyzLatin America. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aInternet.  aLatin American digital culture.  aLatin(x).  aconnectivity.  acreative networks.  acyborgs.  adigital aesthetics.  aelectronic literature.  aonline readerships.  asocial media.  atactical media.  atransmediation.  avirality.1 aArriaga, Eduard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedict, Nora C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBundy, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGainza Cortés, Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov